    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Political Involvement in College",
          "textSize": "heading-two"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "After graduating from High School, Montejano began attending Our Lady of the Lake University (OLLU), a private Catholic University on the Westside. This further increased her political involvement, as her classmate Rosie Castro introduced her to new opportunities. This included the Young Democrats, a student organization that encouraged student participation in the political process to increase the election of Democrat candidates. The Young Democrats exposed Montejano to life in Texas outside of the Mexican American communities in San Antonio, where she discovered the intense discrimination people of color faced in the rest of the state firsthand."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "During this time, Montejano also discovered La Raza Unida (LRUP), a Chicano political party active in the 1970s. The meetings she attended with Raza Unida exposed her to even more Chicano organizations, such as the Mexican American Unity Council (MAUC) and the Mexican American Youth Organization (MAYO). It was also how she was able to participate in the Crystal City boycotts in south Texas. Because she was in school to become a bilingual education teacher, she received the opportunity to volunteer with the students who had walked out of the Crystal City schools to ensure that they were still receiving an education exercising their right protest. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
